{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on real git rename detection and CLI subprocess interaction, not just local classification logic. A stubbed diff can miss failures where real git emits rename vs add/delete differently. System is required to verify the real external command contract on happy path.","test_description":"Create a temp git repo, commit baseline, rename a file with content similarity that git detects as rename, run the real CLI via subprocess, and assert stdout report shows the file only in `renamed` and not in `added`/`deleted`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Binary diff handling commonly fails only with real git output/encoding behavior and subprocess I/O boundaries. In-process fakes can hide decode/format issues. This explicitly needs real infrastructure interaction.","test_description":"Create a temp git repo with a committed binary file change (e.g., random bytes image), run the CLI as a subprocess, assert exit code is success and stdout report includes the binary file in the proper count/category.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This relies on real git behavior for an unborn HEAD/no-commit repo and the CLI’s subprocess error handling. Mocked responses can miss actual stderr/exit-code patterns from git.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with no commits, run the CLI via subprocess, and assert successful process completion with an empty structured report (no crash, no traceback).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This is an externally visible end-to-end correctness claim about a real repository’s history. To avoid false confidence, the test must round-trip against real git history and real CLI output, satisfying the System triad happy-path contract verification.","test_description":"Construct a temp repo with known sequence: add, modify, rename, delete across commits; run CLI subprocess; independently compute expected counts from git history in the same repo; assert report counts exactly match expected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Staged vs unstaged semantics are controlled by real git index/worktree state and subprocess outputs. Fakes often miss edge cases in how git reports each state. Real repo + real CLI execution is the lowest reliable level.","test_description":"In a temp repo, create equivalent file changes once as unstaged and once staged, run CLI subprocess for each state, and assert normalized stdout reports are identical.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
